The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Sunday, January 04, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Bharat Sanchar Nigam Ltd (BSNL) today announced a 25 per cent reduction in ISD tariffs for calls to Saudi Arabia. The new tariff would be effective from February 5 to March 10, BSNL said. Against a peak rate of Rs 24 per minute and an off-peak rate of Rs 21.18 per minute at present, the new Haj tariff would be Rs 18 per minute on a four-second pulse. Telephones would be provided at airport terminals of Bangalore, Srinagar, Calcutta, Gaya, Ahmedabad, Hyderabad and Chennai for Haj pilgrims for free calls within the state.																								 Acer India, a branded PC vendor, plans to have 50 retail stores across the country by January. The company opened its first outlet in Bangalore, which marked its foray into retail distribution. Acer proposed to have Acer malls and Acer point stores in Coimbatore, Lucknow, Kochi, Chandigarh, Ahmedabad, Nagpur, Pune and Hyderabad, besides the four metros, the company said.																								 Gail has launched a nationwide natural gas conservation programme in Delhi. Under the programme, Gail will provide assistance on conservation of natural gas to the power, fertiliser, steel, sponge iron, transport, glass, ceramic and petrochemical industries.																								 Autumnal Sikkimese tea from Temi Tea Estate has fetched the highest price at the Calcutta tea auction sale 50. Golden Tips Tea Co has bought the tea at Rs 820 per kg.																								 BPL has introduced i-Sort function in select 21-inch pure flat matrix range and 20-inch television models. This innovative feature enables viewers to manually sort and retrieve favourite channels under four groups  sports, movie, news and music. The user can then tune into any of the 40 channels without surfing through all the channels available. ADVERTISEMENT
